WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.960
All righty. So as we know, patients with classic Hodgkin lymphoma that relapse after autologous

00:00:09.960 --> 00:00:15.000
stem cell transplant have historically poor outcomes, and recurrence often occurs at the

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.200
site of disease relapse prior to transplant. So as a result, clinicians may utilize peritransplant

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:27.120
radiation to involve sites, sites of bulky disease, and to areas with less than CR prior

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:33.400
to transplant. And what we see in retrospective studies is that this approach does improve local

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:38.700
disease control, but the evidence supporting a PFS and OS benefit is less well-defined.

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:44.480
And then importantly, the role of peritransplant radiation in the era of novel immunotherapy is

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:50.620
unclear. So to better inform our use of peritransplant radiation, we conducted a

00:00:50.620 --> 00:00:56.620
multi-center retrospective study, and specifically we collaborated with five U.S. academic institutions

00:00:56.620 --> 00:00:57.100
to create a study that showed that peritransplant radiation can be used to improve local disease

00:00:57.100 --> 00:01:07.380
control. And we identified patients treated with transplant from 2010, that should say 2023,

00:01:08.380 --> 00:01:12.540
and we defined peritransplant radiation as radiation administered within three months

00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:18.800
of transplant before or after. And we compared the post-transplant PFS and OS between the two

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:27.040
groups, and also looked at treatment trends over the years. So in total, we identified just under

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:27.080
30,000 patients with classic Hodgkin lymphoma. And we identified patients treated with transplant

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:31.480
over the years. So in total, we identified just under 1,300 patients. 1,008 did not receive

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:37.640
peritransplant radiation, and 284 did. And here I'm highlighting the baseline variables that were

00:01:37.640 --> 00:01:42.320
significantly associated with receipt of peritransplant radiation. And those included

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:46.920
early-stage disease at relapse, bulky disease at relapse, which we defined as greater than five

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:51.860
centimeters, primary refractory disease, more than one line of salvage before transplant,

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:56.960
and then less than CR prior to transplant. And then conversely on this,

00:01:57.060 --> 00:02:01.360
I'm just showing the baseline variables that were significantly associated with no receipt

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:06.600
of peritransplant radiation. And this included extra nodal disease at relapse,

00:02:06.600 --> 00:02:13.440
B symptoms at relapse, radiation at initial diagnosis, checkpoint inhibitor in combination

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:20.280
with anything at any point during salvage, and BV maintenance. As I said, we also looked at

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.040
treatment trends, and we defined treatment eras as pre-BV approval, post-BV approval,

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:31.580
BV approval, and post-checkpoint inhibitor approval. And what you can see here is between

00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:36.380
the pre-BV and post-BV approval, there was really no difference in the utilization of

00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:41.320
peritransplant radiation. But after the approval of checkpoint inhibitors in 2016,

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:46.820
in the relapse refractory setting, you can see that the utilization of peritransplant radiation

00:02:46.820 --> 00:02:55.580
halved from 31% to 15%. In our univariable analysis, we can see that the patients that

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:57.020
did receive peritransplant radiation had a higher rate of peritransplant radiation than

00:02:57.020 --> 00:03:02.140
those who did not receive peritransplant radiation. So those shown in green had superior PFS and OS

00:03:02.140 --> 00:03:09.100
compared to those who did not, shown in blue. And this association between radiation and PFS and OS

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:12.220
was significant, shown by these hazard ratios at the bottom.

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:21.820
And then after controlling for several clinically relevant variables in our multivariable analysis,

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:27.000
we saw that this relationship between PFS and peritransplant radiation held true. And

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:27.080
then after controlling for several clinically relevant variables in our multivariable analysis,

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:27.100
we saw that this relationship between PFS and peritransplant radiation held true. And

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:27.100
then after controlling for several clinically relevant variables in our multivariable analysis,

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:27.140
we saw that this relationship between PFS and peritransplant radiation held true. And

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:27.160
then after controlling for several clinically relevant variables in our multivariable analysis,

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:27.180
we saw that this relationship between PFS and peritransplant radiation held true. And

00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:33.720
however, this association between peritransplant radiation and overall survival was lost,

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:36.520
and so we can see that in the bottom row of this box.

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:44.920
We also did an interaction effect analysis, taking into consideration variables that may

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:50.440
be considered when choosing peritransplant radiation. So this included bulky disease relapse,

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:55.800
the salvage regimen, and less than CR prior to transplant. And what we saw was that there was

00:03:55.800 --> 00:04:02.600
no significant interaction between peritransplant radiation and these variables with PFS,

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:06.440
which is in that first column, and OS, which is in that second column.

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:19.000
Nevertheless, we were still interested in whether or not there was some difference in the effect

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:25.240
that peritransplant radiation had based on the salvage regimen. And so we did an additional sub

00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:25.780
group experiment. And we did an additional sub group experiment. And we did an additional sub

00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:35.760
exploratory analysis looking at PFS based on the salvage regimen. And what you can clearly see

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:41.400
here is that the patients who only got chemo in salvage, so that's the curve on the far left,

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:46.520
seemed to benefit the most from peritransplant radiation. And this is in comparison to the

00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:53.880
patients who got BV in combination with chemotherapy, plus or minus, as well as the

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:55.760
patients who got checkpoint radiation, plus or minus, as well as the patients who got checkpoint

00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:59.980
inhibitor at any time point in salvage, which is shown on the far right.

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:09.140
Okay. I'm going quicker than I thought. So in conclusion, I think the big takeaways from this

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:13.540
is that we were able to show that there was a significant association between peritransplant

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:19.660
radiation and PFS. And although we did show an association with overall survival in our

00:05:19.660 --> 00:05:25.740
univariate analysis, this was lost in multivariate analysis. And then there was no significant

00:05:25.740 --> 00:05:31.280
interaction between peritransplant radiation and bulky disease salvage regimen and pre-transplant

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:38.480
response with PFS and OS. And we saw decreased utilization of peritransplant radiation in the

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:45.420
patients receiving checkpoint inhibitors. And those patients seem to derive the least amount

00:05:45.420 --> 00:05:51.700
of benefit from peritransplant radiation. So some prospective validation is warranted.
